               <head/>
               <msContents class=" http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2010102863">
                  <summary>1 copy of Hazār Dhrupad by Nāyak Bakhshū</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="Uk_RSPA_69-item1">
                     <locus from="1v" to="211v"/>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_21938">Hazār Dhrupad</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_21938">هزار دهرپد</title>
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f3232">Nāyak Bakhshū</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" key="person_f3232">نایک بخشو</persName>
                     </author>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa">الله اکبر. وچون نقوس مقدسه تجرد نهاد را میل بلذات روحانی</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">ادتر آدت کاهی ابیات</explicit>
                     <note>
                        <p>This is a collection of 1004 dhrupad (traditional north-Indian musical genre) composed by <persName key="person_f3232" role="aut">Nāyak Bakhshū</persName> (active in the 16th century) which were translated into Persian under the direction of <persName key="viaf_13108102" role="pat">Shāh Jahān</persName>, to whom the work is dedicated and whose name is introduced in every chorus. 
                        </p>
                        <p>The final folio (f211v) bears a seal from 1109AH of a man called <persName key="viaf_71126964" role="asn">Qābil Khān</persName> in the court of <persName key="viaf_6178410" role="oth">Aurangzeb</persName>. 
                        </p>
                     </note>
                     <decoNote>There is a blue and gold headpiece on f1v. </decoNote>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
